Now she looks forward to moving to the United States and going to college.

"I want to go to school and (have) a degree and help my community in Yemen, said Amir, adding that her brother wants to be the first cardiologist in Yemen.

"I feel more comfortable (when called) by my first name," she said, wearing a familiar American take on the abaya, the editor's scarf, and abaya-style coat, which she bought at Melrose.

By now she speaks good English -- especially slang. And her six brothers use websites to find friends in the United States. That way they can learn English with people they know and tell them about Yemen.

In a display of affection, a light hug and a peck on the cheek, Rita, 16, and Hassam Zakariay, 11, of Lebanon, treated their mother, in jeans and T-shirt, to a rose. Their uncle and two of their sisters, too small to make the journey to Bahrain, clutched Rouwa's scarf, and her eldest daughter, Feda, 17, wore a Saudi abaya.

Rouwa's lunch usually includes Yemeni food, but sometimes she likes American spaghetti or macaroni and cheese.
